Understanding the Windows Azure Fabric Controller
The Fabric Controller (FC) is the “kernel” of the distributed operating system, called the Cloud operating system. The FC manages Windows Azure services and datacenter hardware.
The FC takes as inputs a description of the datacenter hardware and network resources it will control. The FC also accepts the service package and data, or binaries, from hosted cloud services.

The FC multi-instance synchronization feature supports rolling
services to continue to run in the event an FC becomes inoperative.

Multi-instance synchronization makes it possible to change, remove, and replace an instance while the system is running without degradation of services or data. Rolling upgrades and replacements of hardware and software are possible, due to multi-instance synchronization.
The FC maintains service health by monitoring the heartbeats of roles and nodes.

The FC programs load balancers to probe a guest agent (GA) every 15 seconds. A “get” command is sent to the guest agent through its assigned virtual IP address. If the guest agent misses 2 probes, the load balancer stops forwarding traffic.
If the role reports a status of “busy” to the guest agent, the GA stops responding to probes.
The node health index algorithm is based on heartbeats and timeouts. The minimum time possible to detect a problem is equal to the sum of the heartbeat, plus the health timeout.
When the node health index falls below zero, the FC attempts to heal the node.
